  <h2 id="faq">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

  <div class="space-y-6 my-8">
    <div class="border-b border-neutral-200 pb-4">
      <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Can I switch from SafetyWing to Cigna later?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600">
        Yes, but with caveats. Any conditions you develop while on SafetyWing become pre-existing conditions when you apply to Cigna. Cigna will underwrite them—possibly excluding them or adding premium. If you know you'll eventually want comprehensive insurance, starting earlier (while healthy) makes sense. Every year you wait with minimal coverage is a year you might develop something that affects future insurability.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="border-b border-neutral-200 pb-4">
      <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Is SafetyWing Nomad accepted for visa applications?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600">
        Sometimes. Some countries (especially EU Schengen) require specific coverage amounts and may not accept travel medical insurance for long-term visas. Portugal's D7 visa, for example, often requires proof of health insurance—SafetyWing Nomad may not qualify. Cigna or SafetyWing Remote Health would. Check your specific visa requirements before choosing.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="border-b border-neutral-200 pb-4">
      <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">What happens if I get sick with SafetyWing and need ongoing care?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600">
        SafetyWing Nomad covers the emergency treatment but not ongoing care. If you're hospitalized for appendicitis, the surgery is covered. Follow-up appointments and medications beyond the acute phase may not be. For chronic conditions diagnosed while covered, you'd need to upgrade to Remote Health (with a waiting period) or purchase other insurance—and the new condition becomes pre-existing.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="border-b border-neutral-200 pb-4">
      <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Does Cigna cover US healthcare if I'm based abroad?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600">
        Yes, with the US coverage add-on (which increases premiums 40-60%). You can also get limited US coverage for emergencies during visits without the full add-on. If you're American returning home occasionally, clarify exactly what's covered during US visits. Cigna offers various configurations.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="border-b border-neutral-200 pb-4">
      <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Can I use both together?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600">
        Technically yes, though it rarely makes sense. Some people keep SafetyWing Nomad as backup while building up Cigna coverage during waiting periods, but you can't double-claim. The coordination of benefits rules mean one insurer is always primary. It's usually simpler to pick one.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="border-b border-neutral-200 pb-4">
      <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Which is better for families with children?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600">
        Cigna, clearly. Kids need routine healthcare: vaccinations, checkups, pediatric visits for ear infections and fevers. SafetyWing Nomad only covers emergencies—fine for healthy adults, inadequate for children who need regular care. Cigna's family discounts also make it more economical for families.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

